ownership of Dover as credit from Stephen. \"Received of my brother Stephen St. John, the one half of his Negro boy named Dover, now inlisted into the Continental Service, for the one half of which boy I am obliged to pay sixty dollars on demand, to exempt me from all actual service. William St. John.\" William was a Loyalist; his wife's 1800 census shows 1 enslaved person still in household."}],"gender":"male","number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"cross_connections":[],"education":[{"notes":"A.B. 1766, A.M. 1769. Same class as Jared Ingersoll and Jonathan Ingersoll.","school_name":"Yale College","graduation_year":1766,"institution_id":"INST022"}],"bio":{"display_name":"William St. John","first_name":"William","last_name":"St. John","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST022","relationship":"alumnus","years":"1762-1766","institution_blurb":"Yale A.B. 1766, A.M. 1769 — same class as Hons. Jared and Jonathan Ingersoll of Connecticut."}],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"former_ids":["HD0368"],"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM002","plot_notes":"East Norwalk Historical Cemetery. FA confirmation."},"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"education","header":"Yale class of 1766","body":"William Saint John graduated Yale with A.B. 1766 and A.M. 1769, in the same class as Hon. Jared and Jonathan Ingersoll — two of Connecticut's most prominent legal and political figures — and served as private tutor in the wealthy Phillipse family of Phillipse, New York. He was described by contemporaries as 'a very fine looking, superior man, a person of fine address and manners, presiding handsomely at his own table.'"},{"number":2,"category":"legacy","header":"Two verdicts: DAR Patriot Ancestor and colonial Loyalist","body":"One chronicler records that Saint John 'was a Loyalist and was sent to New York with the Army,' yet he is simultaneously honored as a DAR Patriot Ancestor (A099267) for Civil Service during the Revolution — a tension common among colonial Norwalk families divided by the conflict. In June 1777 he received from his brother Stephen 'the one half of his Negro boy named Dover, now inlisted into the Continental Service,' paying sixty dollars to exempt himself from actual military service."},{"number":3,"category":"death","header":"Suffered heavy losses when Tryon burned Norwalk, 1779","body":"William Saint John suffered significant property losses in General Tryon's burning of Norwalk in July 1779, the same raid that destroyed or damaged much of the town. He died February 1, 1800, in his fifty-sixth year — survived by his wife Mary Esther Belden, who would outlive him by fifty years, dying at ninety-seven in 1850."}],"slug":"william-st-john-1744"},"X00217":{"id":"X00217","has_descendants_documented":false,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"tags":["slaveholder","moral_complexity"],"sources":[],"birth":{"year":1753},"death":{"year":1850},"gender":"female","number_of_marriages":1,"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"H00481","date_year":1777,"date_month":6,"date_day":19,"children_ids":["H01241","H01242","H01246","H01243","H01244","H01245"]}],"parents":{},"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Mary Esther Belden","first_name":"Mary","middle_name":"Esther","maiden_name":"Belden","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"slug":"mary-belden-1753"},"X00215":{"id":"X00215","has_descendants_documented":false,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"tags":[],"sources":[{"label":"St. John Genealogy (Alexander, 1907)","url":"https://ia601308.us.archive.org/2/items/stjohngenealogyd00lcalex/stjohngenealogyd00lcalex.pdf"}],"birth":{"year":1703},"death":{"year":1756},"gender":"male","number_of_marriages":1,"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"H00253","date_year":1733,"children_ids":["HD0364","H00479","H00478","HD0367","H00481","H00482"]}],"parents":{},"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"cross_connections":[],"bio":{"display_name":"Captain Joseph St. John","first_name":"Joseph","last_name":"St. John","title":"Captain","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"character","header":"Earned 'Blue Sheep' nickname by dyeing his flock","body":"Tradition holds that Capt. Joseph Saint John attempted to dye a sheep blue to create a matching flock — and the rains washed it out, leaving him with the lasting nickname 'The Blue Sheep.' He was a large landowner in Norwalk and among its founding civic leaders, serving as Selectman, Rate Constable, Fence Viewer, and Captain of the 1st Company of the Norwalk trainband (1748)."},{"number":2,"category":"legacy","header":"Wife Susanna's epitaph: Rachel's face, Leah's fruitful womb","body":"When Susanna Selleck Saint John died in December 1749 at forty, Capt. Joseph commissioned a tombstone epitaph comparing her to Rachel ('face'), Leah ('fruitful womb'), Abigail ('wisdom'), Lydia ('faithful heart'), and Martha ('care'). The epitaph — one of the most elaborate in the East Norwalk churchyard — captures how colonial Norwalk elites memorialized women through accumulated biblical virtues."}],"slug":"joseph-st-john-1703"},"H00253":{"id":"H00253","has_descendants_documented":true,"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":true,"generation_from_thomas":5,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1709,"month":9,"day":3,"city":"Stamford","state":"Connecticut"},"death":{"year":1749,"month":12,"day":4,"city":"Norwalk","state":"Connecticut"},"burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM002","plot_notes":"East Norwalk Historical Cemetery, Norwalk, Fairfield, Connecticut"},"parents":{"father_id":"I00129","mother_id":"H00094"},"marriages":[{"children_ids":["HD0364","H00479","H00478","HD0367","H00481","H00482"],"spouse_id":"X00215","marriage_number":1,"date_year":1733}],"gravestone_inscription":"Susanna St. John, ye wife of Capt. Joseph St. John died December ye 4th, 1749 aged 40 years and 2 months. \"She that lies at rest within this tomb / Had Rachel's face and Leah's fruitful womb, / Abigail's wisdom, Lydia's faithful heart / With Martha's care — we hope Mary's better part.\"","tags":[],"sources":[{"short":"Edward Hooker 1909","page":"Entry 253"}],"enslaved_persons":[{"name":"Jenny","description":"Enslaved woman. Listed in estate inventory of Joseph St. John, Dec 7, 1756."},{"name":"London","description":"Enslaved man. Listed in estate inventory of Joseph St. John, Dec 7, 1756."},{"name":"Peter","description":"Enslaved boy. Listed in estate inventory of Joseph St. John, Dec 7, 1756."}],"cross_connections":[],"gender":"female","number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":false,"notable_category":[]},"bio":{"display_name":"Susannah Selleck St. John","first_name":"Susannah","last_name":"St. John","married_names":["St. John"],"maiden_name":"Selleck"},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"military_service":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"family","header":"Her mother died one month after her birth","body":"She was born September 3, 1709 in Norwalk. Her mother Hannah Hooker died October 5, 1709 — barely one month later, age nineteen, of complications from childbirth."},{"number":2,"category":"marriage","header":"Married 'The Blue Sheep' captain in 1729","body":"She married Capt. Joseph St. John in 1729 — known as 'The Blue Sheep' for the local tradition that he once dyed a sheep blue, though the rains washed it out. He served as Norwalk selectman seven times across thirty years."},{"number":3,"category":"social_reform","header":"Three generations of slaveholding descendants","body":"After her death, her husband's 1756 estate inventory listed three enslaved people: Jenny, London, and Peter. Three consecutive generations of her descendants held enslaved people — including grandson William St. John, who sent his enslaved man Dover to the Continental Army in his own place."}],"slug":"susannah-st-john-1709"}},"burialCemetery":{"id":"CEM375","name":"Saint Pauls Cemetery","city":"Norwalk","state":"Connecticut","country":"United States","primary_url":"https://www.findagrave.com/cemetery/103686/saint-pauls-cemetery","hooker_connections":["HD2789","I00714","H01242","X00220"],"notes":"Norwalk Fairfield County CT. Burial site of Judge Benjamin Isaacs (HD2789) and Frances Bryan Isaacs (I00714)."},"institutionsById":{},"crossConnections":[]}